d a Goat -- tThe Chickens Who Wanted to Learn Yiddish -- tPart VII. In Life’s Classroom -- tQuestions -- tBoots and the Bath Squad -- tThe Girl in the Mailbox -- t??? -- tMoe and Nicky -- tRoosteroo -- tPart VIII. Jewish Families, Here and There -- tFrom Labzik: Stories of a Clever Pup -- tLabzik and Glikl -- tEvie Gets Lost -- tMirele’s Birthday -- tFrom An Unusual Girl from Brooklyn -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustration Credits -- tOriginal Sources -- tAbout the Editor and Translator0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn unprecedented treasury of Yiddish children’s stories and poems enhanced with original illustrationsWhile there has been a recent boom in Jewish literacy and learning within the US, few resources exist to enable American Jews to experience the rich primary sources of Yiddish culture. Stepping into this void, Miriam Udel has crafted an exquisite collection: Honey on the Page offers a feast of beguiling original translations of stories and poems for children. Arranged thematically—from school days to the holidays—the book takes readers from Jewish holidays and history to folktales and fables, from stories of humanistic ethics to multi-generational family sagas. Featuring many works that are appearing in English for the first time, and written by both prominent and lesser-known authors, this anthology spans the Yiddish-speaking globe—drawing from materials published in Eastern Europe, New York, and Latin America from the 1910s, during the interwar period, and up through the 1970s. With its vast scope, Honey on the Page offers a cornucopia of delights to families, individuals and educators seeking literature that speaks to Jewish children about their religious, cultural, and ethical heritage.Complemented by a dozen whimsical, humorous illustrations by Paula Cohen, an acclaimed children’s book illustrator, Udel’s evocative translations of Yiddish stories and poetry will delight young and older readers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAuthors, YiddishvBiography. 0aChildren's literature, YiddishvTranslations into English. 7aJUVENILE FICTION / Religious / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aAlkvit, B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsch, Sholem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBastomski, Solomon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElbe, Leon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFichmann, Yaakov, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeltman, Simkhe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutyanski, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIgnatov, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKipnis, Levin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKulbak, Moyshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKvitko, Leyb, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiebert, Sarah L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaze, Ida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMetzker, Isaac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMolodowsky, Kadya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOyerbakh, B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPat, Yankev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaver, Khaver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabinowitz, Zina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReisfeder, Jacob, econtributor.4